Step 1: Create JDBC Repository
This class talks to the database.
What it does
•	Uses JdbcTemplate to execute SQL
•	Runs an INSERT query
Key points
•	@Repository → marks DB layer
•	JdbcTemplate → executes SQL
•	update() → used for INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE
@Repository
public class CourseJdbcRepository {

    @Autowired
    private JdbcTemplate jdbcTemplate;

    private static final String INSERT_QUERY = """
        INSERT INTO course (id, name, author)
        VALUES (1, 'Learn AWS', 'in28minutes')
    """;

    public void insert() {
        jdbcTemplate.update(INSERT_QUERY);
    }
}
________________________________________
Step 2: Run query at application startup
Use CommandLineRunner.
What it does
•	Runs code when Spring Boot starts
•	Calls the repository insert() method
@Component
public class CourseJdbcCommandLineRunner implements CommandLineRunner {

    @Autowired
    private CourseJdbcRepository repository;

    @Override
    public void run(String... args) {
        repository.insert();
    }
}
________________________________________
Step 3: Common mistake (you faced this)
❌ JdbcTemplate was null
Why?
You forgot @Autowired on JdbcTemplate.
Fix
@Autowired
private JdbcTemplate jdbcTemplate;
________________________________________
Step 4: Verify in H2 Console
1.	Open H2 console
2.	Connect using JDBC URL
3.	Run:
SELECT * FROM course;
✅ You will see:
1 | Learn AWS | in28minutes
________________________________________
Summary (Very Simple)
•	JdbcTemplate → executes SQL
•	@Repository → DB layer
•	CommandLineRunner → runs code at startup
•	@Autowired → injects dependencies
•	update() → runs INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE

